    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Abuse of Heroin, All Around</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Open Society Institute president Aryeh Neier letter on Apr 24 article calls for needle exchange and methadone therapy programs to curb spread of AIDS in Siberia associated with injected-drug use</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Heroin Carries AIDS to a Region in Siberia'' (front page, April 24): H.I.V. infection in Russia and its neighbors is fueled almost entirely by injected-drug use. These countries now face the devastating damage done to Africa and parts of Southeast Asia by the global AIDS epidemic. But there is a small window of opportunity to act before the epidemic outpaces the capacity to control it.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Heroin Carries AIDS to a Region in Siberia'' (front page, April 24): H.I.V. infection in Russia and its neighbors is fueled almost entirely by injected-drug use. These countries now face the devastating damage done to Africa and parts of Southeast Asia by the global AIDS epidemic. But there is a small window of opportunity to act before the epidemic outpaces the capacity to control it.</p>
        <p>To do so, more national decision-makers, foreign aid agencies and nongovernment organizations must provide financial and policy support for pragmatic harm-reduction strategies. We have the capability: needle exchanges and methadone therapy are effective public health interventions.</p>
        <p>ARYEH  NEIER  Pres., Open Society Institute  New York, April 26, 2000</p>
      </block>
